06094nam a22008775i 9780812204544DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112006pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979740933  a97808122045447 a10.9783/97808122045442doi  a(DE-B1597)449329  a(OCoLC)759158225  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aLIT0110002bisacsh04a274.050821 aWarren, Nancy Bradley, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWomen of God and Arms :bFemale Spirituality and Political Conflict, 1380-1600 /cNancy Bradley Warren. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b6 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Monastic Politics: St. Colette of Corbie, Franciscan Reform, and the House of Burgundy -- t2. Strategic Saints and Diplomatic Devotion: Margaret of York, Anne d’Orléans, and Female Political Action -- t3. The Sword and the Cloister: Joan of Arc, Margaret of Anjou, and Christine de Pizan in England, 1445–1540 -- t4. Religion and Female Rule: Isabel of Castile and the Construction of Queenship -- t5. The Mystic, the Monarch, and the Persistence of “the Medieval”: Elizabeth Barton and Henry VIII -- t6. Dissolution, Diaspora, and DeWning Englishness: Syon in Exile and Elizabethan Politics -- tConclusion: The Power of the Past -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe religious and political spheres of the later medieval and early modern periods were tightly and indisputably interwoven, as illustrated by the papal schism, the Hundred Years War, the Reconquest of Spain, and the English Reformation. In these events as well as in the larger religiopolitical systems in which they unfolded, female saints, devout lay women, and monastic women played central roles. In Women of God and Arms, Nancy Bradley Warren explores the political dimensions of the religious practices of women ranging from St. Colette of Corbie to Isabel of Castile to English nuns exiled during the reign of Elizabeth I.Just as religious and political systems were bound up with one another, so too were the internal and external politics of England and several continental realms. Blood and marriage connected the English dynasties of Lancaster and York with those of France, Burgundy, Flanders, and Castile, creating tangled networks of alliances and animosities. In addition to being linked through ties of kinship, these realms were joined by frequent textual and cultural exchanges. Warren draws upon a wide variety of sources—hagiography, chronicles, monastic records, devotional treatises, military manuals, political propaganda, and texts traditionally designated as literary—as she examines the ways manifestations of female spirituality operated at the intersections of civic, international, and ecclesiastical politics. Her exploration breaches boundaries separating the medieval and the early modern, the religious and the secular, the material and the symbolic, the literary and the historical, as it sheds new light on well-known figures such as Joan of Arc, Isabel of Castile, and Elizabeth I.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aChristian womenxPolitical activityzEuropexHistoryx16th century. 0aChristian womenxPolitical activityzEuropexHistoryxTo 1500. 0aChristian womenxPolitical activityzEuropexHistoryy16th century. 0aChristian womenxPolitical activityzEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aChristian womenxReligious lifezEuropexHistoryx16th century. 0aChristian womenxReligious lifezEuropexHistoryxTo 1500. 0aChristian womenxReligious lifezEuropexHistoryy16th century. 0a